[src:apache-pulsar/publish-subscribe-pattern] In software architecture, the **publish–subscribe pattern** (**pub/sub**) is a messaging pattern in which message senders, called **publishers**, categorize messages into classes (or *topics*), and send them without needing to know which components will receive them.
[src:apache-pulsar/publish-subscribe-pattern] Message recipients, called **subscribers**, express interest in one or more classes and only receive messages in those classes, without needing to know the identity of the publishers.
[src:apache-pulsar/publish-subscribe-pattern] This pattern decouples the components that produce messages from those that consume them, and supports asynchronous, many-to-many communication.
[src:apache-pulsar/publish-subscribe-pattern] The publish–subscribe model is commonly contrasted with message queue-based and point-to-point messaging models, where producers send messages directly to consumers.
[src:apache-pulsar/publish-subscribe-pattern] Publish–subscribe is a sibling of the message queue paradigm, and is typically a component of larger message-oriented middleware systems.
[src:apache-pulsar/publish-subscribe-pattern] Many modern messaging frameworks and protocols, such as the Java Message Service (JMS), Apache Kafka, and MQTT, support both the pub/sub and queue-based models.
[src:apache-pulsar/publish-subscribe-pattern] This pattern provides greater network scalability and supports more dynamic topologies, but can make it harder to modify the publisher’s logic or the structure of the published data.
[src:apache-pulsar/publish-subscribe-pattern] Compared to synchronous patterns like RPC and point-to-point messaging, publish–subscribe provides the highest level of decoupling among architectural components.
[src:apache-pulsar/publish-subscribe-pattern] However, it can also lead to semantic or format coupling between publishers and subscribers, which may cause systems to become entangled or brittle over time.
[src:apache-pulsar/publish-subscribe-pattern] In publish–subscribe systems, subscribers typically receive only a subset of messages.
[src:apache-pulsar/publish-subscribe-pattern] In most pub/sub systems, publishers and subscribers communicate through a central intermediary such as a message broker or event bus.
[src:apache-pulsar/publish-subscribe-pattern] The broker receives messages from publishers and forwards them to the appropriate subscribers, optionally performing store and forward, priority queuing, or other routing logic.
[src:apache-pulsar/publish-subscribe-pattern] Some pub/sub systems use **brokerless** architectures, in which publishers and subscribers discover each other and exchange messages directly.
[src:apache-pulsar/publish-subscribe-pattern] For example, the Data Distribution Service (DDS) middleware uses IP multicast and metadata sharing to establish communication paths.
[src:apache-pulsar/publish-subscribe-pattern] Brokerless systems require construction of overlay networks, often using Small-World topologies to enable efficient routing.
[src:apache-pulsar/publish-subscribe-pattern] It was shown by Jon Kleinberg that efficient decentralized routing requires Navigable Small-World topologies, which are employed in federated or peer-to-peer pub/sub systems.
[src:apache-pulsar/publish-subscribe-pattern] Locality-aware pub/sub networks use low-latency links to reduce message propagation time.
[src:apache-pulsar/publish-subscribe-pattern] One of the earliest publicly described pub/sub systems was the "news" subsystem of the Isis Toolkit, presented at the 1987 ACM Symposium on Operating Systems Principles (SOSP '87).
[src:apache-pulsar/publish-subscribe-pattern] As distributed systems became more common, the publish–subscribe model evolved to emphasize asynchronous messaging and broker-mediated communication, setting it apart from the more tightly coupled observer pattern.
[src:apache-pulsar/publish-subscribe-pattern] Publishers are loosely coupled to subscribers, and need not even know of their existence.
[src:apache-pulsar/publish-subscribe-pattern] With the topic being the focus, publishers and subscribers are allowed to remain ignorant of system topology.
[src:apache-pulsar/publish-subscribe-pattern] Each can continue to operate as per normal independently of the other.
[src:apache-pulsar/publish-subscribe-pattern] In the traditional tightly coupled client–server paradigm, the client cannot post messages to the server while the server process is not running, nor can the server receive messages unless the client is running.
[src:apache-pulsar/publish-subscribe-pattern] Many pub/sub systems decouple not only the locations of the publishers and subscribers but also decouple them temporally.
[src:apache-pulsar/publish-subscribe-pattern] A common strategy used by middleware analysts with such pub/sub systems is to take down a publisher to allow the subscriber to work through the backlog (a form of bandwidth throttling).
[src:apache-pulsar/publish-subscribe-pattern] Pub/sub provides the opportunity for better scalability than traditional client-server, through parallel operation, message caching, tree-based or network-based routing, etc.
[src:apache-pulsar/publish-subscribe-pattern] Outside of the enterprise environment, on the other hand, the pub/sub paradigm has proven its scalability to volumes far beyond those of a single data center, providing Internet-wide distributed messaging through web syndication protocols such as RSS and Atom.
[src:apache-pulsar/publish-subscribe-pattern] These syndication protocols accept higher latency and lack of delivery guarantees in exchange for the ability for even a low-end web server to syndicate messages to (potentially) millions of separate subscriber nodes.
[src:apache-pulsar/publish-subscribe-pattern] Redundant subscribers in a pub/sub system can help assure message delivery with minimal additional complexity.
[src:apache-pulsar/publish-subscribe-pattern] For example, a factory may utilize a pub/sub system where equipment can publish problems or failures to a subscriber that displays and logs those problems.
[src:apache-pulsar/publish-subscribe-pattern] If the logger fails (crashes), equipment problem publishers won't necessarily receive notice of the logger failure, and error messages will not be displayed or recorded by any equipment on the pub/sub system.
[src:apache-pulsar/publish-subscribe-pattern] In a client/server system, when an error logger fails, the system will receive an indication of the error logger (server) failure.
[src:apache-pulsar/publish-subscribe-pattern] However, the client/server system will have to deal with that failure by having redundant logging servers online, or by dynamically spawning fallback logging servers.
[src:apache-pulsar/publish-subscribe-pattern] This adds complexity to the client and server designs, as well as to the client/server architecture as a whole.
[src:apache-pulsar/publish-subscribe-pattern] In a pub/sub system, redundant logging subscribers that are exact duplicates of the existing logger can be added to the system to increase logging reliability without any impact to any other equipment on the system.
[src:apache-pulsar/publish-subscribe-pattern] The feature of assured error message logging can also be added incrementally, subsequent to implementing the basic functionality of equipment problem message logging.
[src:apache-pulsar/publish-subscribe-pattern] The most serious problems with pub/sub systems are a side-effect of their main advantage: the decoupling of publisher from subscriber.
[src:apache-pulsar/publish-subscribe-pattern] A pub/sub system must be designed carefully to be able to provide stronger system properties that a particular application might require, such as assured delivery.
[src:apache-pulsar/publish-subscribe-pattern] The pub/sub pattern scales well for small networks with a small number of publisher and subscriber nodes and low message volume.
[src:apache-pulsar/publish-subscribe-pattern] However, as the number of nodes and messages grows, the likelihood of instabilities increases, limiting the maximum scalability of a pub/sub network.
[src:apache-pulsar/publish-subscribe-pattern] For pub/sub systems that use brokers (servers), the argument for a broker to send messages to a subscriber is in-band, and can be subject to security problems.
[src:apache-pulsar/publish-subscribe-pattern] Brokers might be fooled into sending notifications to the wrong client, amplifying denial of service requests against the client.
[src:apache-pulsar/publish-subscribe-pattern] Brokers themselves could be overloaded as they allocate resources to track created subscriptions.
[src:apache-pulsar/publish-subscribe-pattern] Even with systems that do not rely on brokers, a subscriber might be able to receive data that it is not authorized to receive.
[src:apache-pulsar/publish-subscribe-pattern] An unauthorized publisher may be able to introduce incorrect or damaging messages into the pub/sub system.
[src:apache-pulsar/publish-subscribe-pattern] This is especially true with systems that broadcast or multicast their messages.
[src:apache-pulsar/publish-subscribe-pattern] Transport Layer Security (SSL/TLS)) can prevent unauthorized access, but cannot prevent damaging messages from being introduced by authorized publishers.
[src:apache-pulsar/publish-subscribe-pattern] Architectures other than pub/sub, such as client/server systems, are also vulnerable to authorized message senders that behave maliciously.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] Replication in space or in time is often linked to scheduling algorithms.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] Access to a replicated entity is typically uniform with access to a single non-replicated entity.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] The replication itself should be transparent to an external user.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] In a failure scenario, a failover of replicas should be hidden as much as possible with respect to quality of service.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] When one leader replica is designated via leader election to process all the requests, the system is using a primary-backup or primary-replica scheme, which is predominant in high-availability clusters.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] In comparison, if any replica can process a request and distribute a new state, the system is using a multi-primary or multi-master scheme.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] In the latter case, some form of distributed concurrency control must be used, such as a distributed lock manager.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] Load balancing differs from task replication, since it distributes a load of different computations across machines, and allows a single computation to be dropped in case of failure.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] Load balancing, however, sometimes uses data replication (especially multi-master replication) internally, to distribute its data among machines.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] Backup differs from replication in that the saved copy of data remains unchanged for a long period of time.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] Replicas, on the other hand, undergo frequent updates and quickly lose any historical state.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] Replication is one of the oldest and most important topics in the overall area of distributed systems.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] Data replication and computation replication both require processes to handle incoming events.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] Processes for data replication are passive and operate only to maintain the stored data, reply to read requests and apply updates.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] Computation replication is usually performed to provide fault-tolerance, and take over an operation if one component fails.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] In both cases, the underlying needs are to ensure that the replicas see the same events in equivalent orders, so that they stay in consistent states and any replica can respond to queries.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] Database replication involves maintaining copies of the same data on multiple machines, typically implemented through three main approaches: single-leader, multi-leader, and leaderless replication.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] In single-leader (also called primary/replica) replication, one database instance is designated as the leader (primary), which handles all write operations.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] The leader logs these updates, which then propagate to replica nodes.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] Each replica acknowledges receipt of updates, enabling subsequent write operations.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] Replicas primarily serve read requests, though they may serve stale data due to replication lag – the delay in propagating changes from the leader.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] In multi-master replication (also called multi-leader), updates can be submitted to any database node, which then propagate to other servers.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] This approach is particularly beneficial in multi-data center deployments, where it enables local write processing while masking inter-data center network latency.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] However, it introduces substantially increased costs and complexity which may make it impractical in some situations.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] The most common challenge that exists in multi-master replication is transactional conflict prevention or resolution when concurrent modifications occur on different leader nodes.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] Most synchronous (or eager) replication solutions perform conflict prevention, while asynchronous (or lazy) solutions have to perform conflict resolution.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] For instance, if the same record is changed on two nodes simultaneously, an eager replication system would detect the conflict before confirming the commit and abort one of the transactions.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] A lazy replication system would allow both transactions to commit and run a conflict resolution during re-synchronization.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] Conflict resolution methods can include techniques like last-write-wins, application-specific logic, or merging concurrent updates.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] However, replication transparency can not always be achieved.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] When data is replicated in a database, they will be constrained by CAP theorem or PACELC theorem.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] In the NoSQL movement, data consistency is usually sacrificed in exchange for other more desired properties, such as availability (A), partition tolerance (P), etc.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] Various data consistency models have also been developed to serve as Service Level Agreement (SLA) between service providers and the users.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] Active (real-time) storage replication is usually implemented by distributing updates of a block device to several physical hard disks.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] This way, any file system supported by the operating system can be replicated without modification, as the file system code works on a level above the block device driver layer.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] It is implemented either in hardware (in a disk array controller) or in software (in a device driver).
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] The most basic method is disk mirroring, which is typical for locally connected disks.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] The storage industry narrows the definitions, so *mirroring* is a local (short-distance) operation.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] A replication is extendable across a computer network, so that the disks can be located in physically distant locations, and the primary/replica database replication model is usually applied.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] The purpose of replication is to prevent damage from failures or disasters that may occur in one location – or in case such events do occur, to improve the ability to recover data.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] For replication, latency is the key factor because it determines either how far apart the sites can be or the type of replication that can be employed.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] The main characteristic of such cross-site replication is how write operations are handled, through either asynchronous or synchronous replication; synchronous replication needs to wait for the destination server's response in any write operation whereas asynchronous replication does not.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] Synchronous replication guarantees "zero data loss" by the means of atomic write operations, where the write operation is not considered complete until acknowledged by both the local and remote storage.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] Most applications wait for a write transaction to complete before proceeding with further work, hence overall performance decreases considerably.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] Inherently, performance drops proportionally to distance, as minimum latency is dictated by the speed of light.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] For 10 km distance, the fastest possible roundtrip takes 67 μs, whereas an entire local cached write completes in about 10–20 μs.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] In asynchronous replication, the write operation is considered complete as soon as local storage acknowledges it.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] Remote storage is updated with a small lag.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] Performance is greatly increased, but in case of a local storage failure, the remote storage is not guaranteed to have the current copy of data (the most recent data may be lost).
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] Semi-synchronous replication typically considers a write operation complete when acknowledged by local storage and received or logged by the remote server.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] The actual remote write is performed asynchronously, resulting in better performance but remote storage will lag behind the local storage, so that there is no guarantee of durability (i.e., seamless transparency) in the case of local storage failure.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] Point-in-time replication produces periodic snapshots which are replicated instead of primary storage.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] This is intended to replicate only the changed data instead of the entire volume.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] As less information is replicated using this method, replication can occur over less-expensive bandwidth links such as iSCSI or T1 instead of fiberoptic lines.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] Many distributed filesystems use replication to ensure fault tolerance and avoid a single point of failure.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] Many commercial synchronous replication systems do not freeze when the remote replica fails or loses connection – behaviour which guarantees zero data loss – but proceed to operate locally, losing the desired zero recovery point objective.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] Techniques of wide-area network (WAN) optimization can be applied to address the limits imposed by latency.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] File-based replication conducts data replication at the logical level (i.e., individual data files) rather than at the storage block level.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] There are many different ways of performing this, which almost exclusively rely on software.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] A kernel driver (specifically a filter driver) can be used to intercept calls to the filesystem functions, capturing any activity as it occurs.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] This uses the same type of technology that real-time active virus checkers employ.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] At this level, logical file operations are captured like file open, write, delete, etc.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] The kernel driver transmits these commands to another process, generally over a network to a different machine, which will mimic the operations of the source machine.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] Like block-level storage replication, the file-level replication allows both synchronous and asynchronous modes.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] In synchronous mode, write operations on the source machine are held and not allowed to occur until the destination machine has acknowledged the successful replication.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] Synchronous mode is less common with file replication products although a few solutions exist.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] File-level replication solutions allow for informed decisions about replication based on the location and type of the file.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] For example, temporary files or parts of a filesystem that hold no business value could be excluded.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] The data transmitted can also be more granular; if an application writes 100 bytes, only the 100 bytes are transmitted instead of a complete disk block (generally 4,096 bytes).
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] This substantially reduces the amount of data sent from the source machine and the storage burden on the destination machine.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] Drawbacks of this software-only solution include the requirement for implementation and maintenance on the operating system level, and an increased burden on the machine's processing power.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] Similarly to database transaction logs, many file systems have the ability to journal their activity.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] The journal can be sent to another machine, either periodically or in real time by streaming.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] On the replica side, the journal can be used to play back file system modifications.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] One of the notable implementations is Microsoft's System Center Data Protection Manager (DPM), released in 2005, which performs periodic updates but does not offer real-time replication.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] This is the process of comparing the source and destination file systems and ensuring that the destination matches the source.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] The key benefit is that such solutions are generally free or inexpensive.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] The downside is that the process of synchronizing them is quite system-intensive, and consequently this process generally runs infrequently.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] One of the notable implementations is rsync.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] In a paging operating system, pages in a paging file are sometimes replicated within a track to reduce rotational latency.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] In IBM's VSAM, index data are sometimes replicated within a track to reduce rotational latency.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] Another example of using replication appears in distributed shared memory systems, where many nodes of the system share the same page of memory.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] This usually means that each node has a separate copy (replica) of a specific page.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] Many classical approaches to replication are based on a primary-backup model where one device or process has unilateral control over one or more other processes or devices.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] For example, the primary might perform some computation, streaming a log of updates to a backup (standby) process, which can then take over if the primary fails.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] This approach is common for replicating databases, despite the risk that if a portion of the log is lost during a failure, the backup might not be in a state identical to the primary, and transactions could then be lost.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] A weakness of primary-backup schemes is that only one is actually performing operations.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] Fault-tolerance is gained, but the identical backup system doubles the costs.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] 1985, the distributed systems research community began to explore alternative methods of replicating data.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] An outgrowth of this work was the emergence of schemes in which a group of replicas could cooperate, with each process acting as a backup while also handling a share of the workload.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] Computer scientist Jim Gray analyzed multi-primary replication schemes under the transactional model and published a widely cited paper skeptical of the approach "The Dangers of Replication and a Solution".
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] He argued that unless the data splits in some natural way so that the database can be treated as *n* disjoint sub-databases, concurrency control conflicts will result in seriously degraded performance and the group of replicas will probably slow as a function of *n*.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] Gray suggested that the most common approaches are likely to result in degradation that scales as *O(n³)*.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] His solution, which is to partition the data, is only viable in situations where data actually has a natural partitioning key.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] In the 1985–1987, the virtual synchrony model was proposed and emerged as a widely adopted standard (it was used in the Isis Toolkit, Horus, Transis, Ensemble, Totem, Spread, C-Ensemble, Phoenix and Quicksilver systems, and is the basis for the CORBA fault-tolerant computing standard).
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] Virtual synchrony permits a multi-primary approach in which a group of processes cooperates to parallelize some aspects of request processing.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] The scheme can only be used for some forms of in-memory data, but can provide linear speedups in the size of the group.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] A number of modern products support similar schemes.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] For example, the Spread Toolkit supports this same virtual synchrony model and can be used to implement a multi-primary replication scheme; it would also be possible to use C-Ensemble or Quicksilver in this manner.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] WANdisco permits active replication where every node on a network is an exact copy or replica and hence every node on the network is active at one time; this scheme is optimized for use in a wide area network (WAN).
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] Modern multi-primary replication protocols optimize for the common failure-free operation.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] Chain replication is a popular family of such protocols.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] State-of-the-art protocol variants of chain replication offer high throughput and strong consistency by arranging replicas in a chain for writes.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] This approach enables local reads on all replica nodes but has high latency for writes that must traverse multiple nodes sequentially.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] A more recent multi-primary protocol, Hermes, combines cache-coherent-inspired invalidations and logical timestamps to achieve strong consistency with local reads and high-performance writes from all replicas.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] During fault-free operation, its broadcast-based writes are non-conflicting and commit after just one multicast round-trip to replica nodes.
[src:apache-pulsar/replication-computing] This design results in high throughput and low latency for both reads and writes.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] In computer science, **stream processing** (also known as **event stream processing**, **data stream processing**, or **distributed stream processing**) is a programming paradigm which views streams, or sequences of events in time, as the central input and output objects of computation.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] Stream processing encompasses dataflow programming, reactive programming, and distributed data processing.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] Stream processing systems use streaming algorithms to trace parallel processing for data streams.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] The stream processing paradigm simplifies parallel software and hardware by restricting the parallel computation that can be performed.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] Given a sequence of data (a *stream*), a series of operations (*kernel functions*) is applied to each element in the stream.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] Kernel functions are usually pipelined, and optimal local on-chip memory reuse is attempted, in order to minimize the loss in bandwidth, associated with external memory interaction.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] *Uniform streaming*, where one kernel function is applied to all elements in the stream, is typical.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] Since the kernel and stream abstractions expose data dependencies, compiler tools can fully automate and optimize on-chip management tasks.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] Stream processing hardware can use scoreboarding, for example, to initiate a direct memory access (DMA) when dependencies become known.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] The elimination of manual DMA management reduces software complexity, and an associated elimination for hardware cached I/O, reduces the data area expanse that has to be involved with service by specialized computational units such as arithmetic logic units.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] During the 1980s stream processing was explored within dataflow programming.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] An example is the language SISAL (Streams and Iteration in a Single Assignment Language).
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] Stream processing is essentially a compromise, driven by a data-centric model that works very well for traditional DSP or GPU-type applications (such as image, video and digital signal processing) but less so for general purpose processing with more randomized data access (such as databases).
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] By sacrificing some flexibility in the model, the implications allow easier, faster and more efficient execution.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] Depending on the context, processor design may be tuned for maximum efficiency or a trade-off for flexibility.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] For each record we can only read from the input, perform operations on it, and write to the output.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] It is permissible to have multiple inputs and multiple outputs, but never a piece of memory that is both readable and writable.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] By way of illustration, the following code fragments demonstrate detection of patterns within event streams.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] The first is an example of processing a data stream using a continuous SQL query (a query that executes forever processing arriving data based on timestamps and window duration).
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] This code fragment illustrates a JOIN of two data streams, one for stock orders, and one for the resulting stock trades.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] The query outputs a stream of all Orders matched by a Trade within one second of the Order being placed.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] The output stream is sorted by timestamp, in this case, the timestamp from the Orders stream.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] Another sample code fragment detects weddings among a flow of external "events" such as church bells ringing, the appearance of a man in a tuxedo or morning suit, a woman in a flowing white gown and rice flying through the air.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] A "complex" or "composite" event is what one infers from the individual simple events: a wedding is happening.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] Basic computers started from a sequential execution paradigm.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] Traditional CPUs are SISD based, which means they conceptually perform only one operation at a time.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] As the computing needs of the world evolved, the amount of data to be managed increased very quickly.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] It was obvious that the sequential programming model could not cope with the increased need for processing power.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] Various efforts have been spent on finding alternative ways to perform massive amounts of computations but the only solution was to exploit some level of parallel execution.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] The result of those efforts was SIMD, a programming paradigm which allowed applying one instruction to multiple instances of (different) data.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] Most of the time, SIMD was being used in a SWAR environment.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] By using more complicated structures, one could also have MIMD parallelism.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] Although those two paradigms were efficient, real-world implementations were plagued with limitations from memory alignment problems to synchronization issues and limited parallelism.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] Only few SIMD processors survived as stand-alone components; most were embedded in standard CPUs.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] Consider a simple program adding up two arrays containing 100 4-component vectors (i.e.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] This is the sequential paradigm that is most familiar.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] Variations do exist (such as inner loops, structures and such), but they ultimately boil down to that construct.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] It assumes the instruction `vector_sum` works.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] Although this is what happens with instruction intrinsics, much information is actually not taken into account here such as the number of vector components and their data format.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] You can see however, this method reduces the number of decoded instructions from *numElements * componentsPerElement* to *numElements*.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] The number of jump instructions is also decreased, as the loop is run fewer times.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] These gains result from the parallel execution of the four mathematical operations.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] What happened however is that the packed SIMD register holds a certain amount of data so it's not possible to get more parallelism.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] The speed up is somewhat limited by the assumption we made of performing four parallel operations (please note this is common for both AltiVec and SSE).
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] In this paradigm, the whole dataset is defined, rather than each component block being defined separately.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] Describing the set of data is assumed to be in the first two rows.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] After that, the result is inferred from the sources and kernel.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] For simplicity, there's a 1:1 mapping between input and output data but this does not need to be.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] Applied kernels can also be much more complex.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] An implementation of this paradigm can "unroll" a loop internally.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] This allows throughput to scale with chip complexity, easily utilizing hundreds of ALUs.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] The elimination of complex data patterns makes much of this extra power available.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] While stream processing is a branch of SIMD/MIMD processing, they must not be confused.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] Although SIMD implementations can often work in a "streaming" manner, their performance is not comparable: the model envisions a very different usage pattern which allows far greater performance by itself.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] It has been noted that when applied on generic processors such as standard CPU, only a 1.5x speedup can be reached.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] By contrast, ad-hoc stream processors easily reach over 10x performance, mainly attributed to the more efficient memory access and higher levels of parallel processing.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] Although there are various degrees of flexibility allowed by the model, stream processors usually impose some limitations on the kernel or stream size.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] For example, consumer hardware often lacks the ability to perform high-precision math, lacks complex indirection chains or presents lower limits on the number of instructions which can be executed.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] Stanford University stream processing projects included the Stanford Real-Time Programmable Shading Project started in 1999.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] A prototype called Imagine was developed in 2002.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] A project called Merrimac ran until about 2004.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] AT&T also researched stream-enhanced processors as graphics processing units rapidly evolved in both speed and functionality.[1] Since these early days, dozens of stream processing languages have been developed, as well as specialized hardware.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] The most immediate challenge in the realm of parallel processing does not lie as much in the type of hardware architecture used, but in how easy it will be to program the system in question in a real-world environment with acceptable performance.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] Machines like Imagine use a straightforward single-threaded model with automated dependencies, memory allocation and DMA scheduling.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] This in itself is a result of the research at MIT and Stanford in finding an optimal *layering of tasks* between programmer, tools and hardware.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] Programmers beat tools in mapping algorithms to parallel hardware, and tools beat programmers in figuring out smartest memory allocation schemes, etc.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] Of particular concern are MIMD designs such as Cell, for which the programmer needs to deal with application partitioning across multiple cores and deal with process synchronization and load balancing.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] A drawback of SIMD programming was the issue of array-of-structures (AoS) and structure-of-arrays (SoA).
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] When multiple of these structures exist in memory they are placed end to end creating an arrays in an *array of structures* (AoS) topology.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] This means that should some algorithm be applied to the location of each particle in turn it must skip over memory locations containing the other attributes.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] If these attributes are not needed this results in wasteful usage of the CPU cache.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] Additionally, a SIMD instruction will typically expect the data it will operate on to be contiguous in memory, the elements may also need to be aligned.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] By moving the memory location of the data out of the structure data can be better organised for efficient access in a stream and for SIMD instructions to operate one.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] A *structure of arrays* (SoA), as shown below, can allow this.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] Instead of holding the data in the structure, it holds only pointers (memory locations) for the data.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] Shortcomings are that if multiple attributes to of an object are to be operated on they might now be distant in memory and so result in a cache miss.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] The aligning and any needed padding lead to increased memory usage.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] Overall, memory management may be more complicated if structures are added and removed for example.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] For stream processors, the usage of structures is encouraged.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] From an application point of view, all the attributes can be defined with some flexibility.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] Taking GPUs as reference, there is a set of attributes (at least 16) available.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] For each attribute, the application can state the number of components and the format of the components (but only primitive data types are supported for now).
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] The various attributes are then attached to a memory block, possibly defining a *stride* between 'consecutive' elements of the same attributes, effectively allowing interleaved data.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] When the GPU begins the stream processing, it will *gather* all the various attributes in a single set of parameters (usually this looks like a structure or a "magic global variable"), performs the operations and *scatters* the results to some memory area for later processing (or retrieving).
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] More modern stream processing frameworks provide a FIFO like interface to structure data as a literal stream.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] This abstraction provides a means to specify data dependencies implicitly while enabling the runtime/hardware to take full advantage of that knowledge for efficient computation.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] One of the simplest and most efficient stream processing modalities to date for C++, is RaftLib, which enables linking independent compute kernels together as a data flow graph using C++ stream operators.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] Apart from specifying streaming applications in high-level languages, models of computation (MoCs) also have been widely used as dataflow models and process-based models.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] Historically, CPUs began implementing various tiers of memory access optimizations because of the ever-increasing performance when compared to relatively slow growing external memory bandwidth.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] As this gap widened, big amounts of die area were dedicated to hiding memory latencies.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] Since fetching information and opcodes to those few ALUs is expensive, very little die area is dedicated to actual mathematical machinery (as a rough estimation, consider it to be less than 10%).
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] A similar architecture exists on stream processors but thanks to the new programming model, the amount of transistors dedicated to management is actually very little.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] Beginning from a whole system point of view, stream processors usually exist in a controlled environment.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] GPUs do exist on an add-in board (this seems to also apply to Imagine).
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] CPUs continue do the job of managing system resources, running applications, and such.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] The stream processor is usually equipped with a fast, efficient, proprietary memory bus (crossbar switches are now common, multi-buses have been employed in the past).
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] The exact amount of memory lanes is dependent on the market range.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] As this is written, there are still 64-bit wide interconnections around (entry-level).
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] Most mid-range models use a fast 128-bit crossbar switch matrix (4 or 2 segments), while high-end models deploy huge amounts of memory (actually up to 512 MB) with a slightly slower crossbar that is 256 bits wide.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] By contrast, standard processors from Intel Pentium to some Athlon 64 have only a single 64-bit wide data bus.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] Memory access patterns are much more predictable.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] While arrays do exist, their dimension is fixed at kernel invocation.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] The thing which most closely matches a multiple pointer indirection is an *indirection chain*, which is however guaranteed to finally read or write from a specific memory area (inside a stream).
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] Because of the SIMD nature of the stream processor's execution units (ALUs clusters), read/write operations are expected to happen in bulk, so memories are optimized for high bandwidth rather than low latency (this is a difference from Rambus and DDR SDRAM, for example).
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] This also allows for efficient memory bus negotiations.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] Most (90%) of a stream processor's work is done on-chip, requiring only 1% of the global data to be stored to memory.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] This is where knowing the kernel temporaries and dependencies pays.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] Internally, a stream processor features some clever communication and management circuits but what's interesting is the *Stream Register File* (SRF).
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] This is conceptually a large cache in which stream data is stored to be transferred to external memory in bulks.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] As a cache-like software-controlled structure to the various ALUs, the SRF is shared between all the various ALU clusters.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] The key concept and innovation here done with Stanford's Imagine chip is that the compiler is able to automate and allocate memory in an optimal way, fully transparent to the programmer.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] The dependencies between kernel functions and data is known through the programming model which enables the compiler to perform flow analysis and optimally pack the SRFs.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] Commonly, this cache and DMA management can take up the majority of a project's schedule, something the stream processor (or at least Imagine) totally automates.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] Tests done at Stanford showed that the compiler did an as well or better job at scheduling memory than if you hand tuned the thing with much effort.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] There is proof; there can be a lot of clusters because inter-cluster communication is assumed to be rare.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] Internally however, each cluster can efficiently exploit a much lower amount of ALUs because intra-cluster communication is common and thus needs to be highly efficient.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] To keep those ALUs fetched with data, each ALU is equipped with local register files (LRFs), which are basically its usable registers.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] This three-tiered data access pattern, makes it easy to keep temporary data away from slow memories, thus making the silicon implementation highly efficient and power-saving.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] Although an order of magnitude speedup can be reasonably expected (even from mainstream GPUs when computing in a streaming manner), not all applications benefit from this.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] Communication latencies are actually the biggest problem.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] Although PCI Express improved this with full-duplex communications, getting a GPU (and possibly a generic stream processor) to work will possibly take long amounts of time.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] This means it's usually counter-productive to use them for small datasets.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] Because changing the kernel is a rather expensive operation the stream architecture also incurs penalties for small streams, a behaviour referred to as the *short stream effect*.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] Pipelining is a very widespread and heavily used practice on stream processors, with GPUs featuring pipelines exceeding 200 stages.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] The cost for switching settings is dependent on the setting being modified but it is now considered to always be expensive.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] To avoid those problems at various levels of the pipeline, many techniques have been deployed such as "über shaders" and "texture atlases".
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] Those techniques are game-oriented because of the nature of GPUs, but the concepts are interesting for generic stream processing as well.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] Most programming languages for stream processors start with Java, C or C++ and add extensions which provide specific instructions to allow application developers to tag kernels and/or streams.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] This also applies to most shading languages, which can be considered stream programming languages to a certain degree.
[src:apache-pulsar/stream-processing] Commercial implementations are either general purpose or tied to specific hardware by a vendor.
